Determine the Directed A-cyclic Graph of child->parent relationships between these pages.

Each TAG (and thus input/output file, since those are all 1-on-1 related) in
$PLANROOT/ObjectiveTree/10-refactor-documentation/03-define-information-architecture/02-reference-manual-chapter-map/01-define-the-group-and-page-structure/01-establish-legacy-group-and-page-structure/legacy-overview.md
is associtated with exactly one parent, accept the root node this graph, which is `mainpage`.

Find what that parent is for all other files.
That parent should have at least one link to the child.

Those links are almost certainly `\ref TAG`. In fact, I could find the following:

```
\ref book_allocations_intro
\ref book_writing
\ref chapter_alloc_locations
\ref chapter_attach_gdb
\ref chapter_core_dump
\ref chapter_custom_debug_h
\ref chapter_custom_do
\ref chapter_environment
\ref chapter_gdb
\ref chapter_magic_numbers
\ref chapter_nesting
\ref chapter_rcfile
\ref chapter_symbols_intro
\ref chapter_validation
\ref group_control_flags
\ref group_debug_channels
\ref group_debug_object
\ref group_destination
\ref group_fatal_output
\ref group_finding
\ref group_formatting
\ref group_invisible
\ref group_locations
\ref group_markers
\ref group_overview
\ref group_special
\ref group_type_info
\ref page_why_macro
\ref preparation
```

And the following tags are not refered to by a /ref:

```
book_allocations        modules.dox             group__book__allocations.html
book_runtime            modules.dox             group__book__runtime.html
book_start              modules.dox             group__book__start.html
book_symbols            modules.dox             group__book__symbols.html
book_writing_intro      modules.dox             group__book__writing.html
downloading             downloading.dox         downloading.html
group_alloc_format      alloc_format.dox        group__group__alloc__format.html
group_function          function.dox            group__group__function.html
```

The first five are groups defined by modules.dox (by containing an \addtogroup) and seems to be not link
to from any "parent" page, although they are linked back to from their child pages.

But `alloc_format.dox` contains:
```
\addtogroup group_alloc_format Format Of The Overview Of Allocated Memory
\ingroup group_overview
```
Where the \addtogroup again is responsible for creating the page (group__group__alloc__format.html)
and the \ingroup creates a parent-child relationship where group_overview is the parent of group_alloc_format.

And, I can find the following \ingroup directives:
```
\ingroup book_allocations
\ingroup book_allocations_intro
\ingroup book_start
\ingroup book_symbols
\ingroup book_writing
\ingroup chapter_alloc_locations
\ingroup chapter_attach_gdb
\ingroup chapter_core_dump
\ingroup chapter_custom_debug_h
\ingroup chapter_custom_do
\ingroup chapter_environment
\ingroup chapter_gdb
\ingroup chapter_magic_numbers
\ingroup chapter_nesting
\ingroup chapter_rcfile
\ingroup chapter_symbols_intro
\ingroup chapter_validation
\ingroup group_alloc_format
\ingroup group_control_flags
\ingroup group_debug_channels
\ingroup group_debug_object
\ingroup group_destination
\ingroup group_fatal_output
\ingroup group_finding
\ingroup group_formatting
\ingroup group_function
\ingroup group_invisible
\ingroup group_locations
\ingroup group_markers
\ingroup group_overview
\ingroup group_special
\ingroup group_type_info
```

Not all of those define a parent-child relationship however; for example core_dump.dox
contains:
```
/*!
\defgroup chapter_core_dump Making The Program Dump Core
*/
/*!
\page page_core_dump
\ingroup chapter_core_dump
*/
```
and it seems that the \page isn't doing anything, whereas the \ingroup probably just puts `chapter_core_dump` (the current group) in itself.
At most I'd expect a relationship where chapter_core_dump is the parent of page_core_dump - but well, the latter doesn't exist.

Put the resulting graph in $PLANROOT/current_objective/ in an appropriate form.
If the result is in indeed a pure tree, then I'd prefer it to be listed as a navigation tree, i.e.
```
mainpage
  book_writing_intro
  group_destination
  group_debug_object
    chapter_custom_do
  group_debug_channels
    group_default_dc
  group_control_flags
  group_formatting
...
  group_overview
    group_invisible
...
```
